article.headline: Creighton 66, Wyoming 61
article.story: LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- Creighton kept ahold of its perfect record on Monday, dominating Wyoming most of the way to a 66-61 win. After falling behind in the first couple minutes, the Cowboys (6-4) spent the rest of the game trying to catch up. They advanced to within 3 points with about a minute left, but the effort came too late. Joe Dabbert led the Bluejays (8-0) with 19 points, a career high. "It was one of the more physical games that we have played this year and it was a big road win for us," Creighton head coach Dana Altman said. Wyoming head coach Steve McClain called it undoubtedly the most physical game his team has played this season. He credited the Bluejays with keeping the lid on his players from the start. "They kind of slowed us down and because of that we weren't attacking and that just got us in a rut," he said. "We never could get in a rhythm offensively." He was at a loss to explain Wyoming's sluggish start. The Cowboys fell behind by as much as 30-19 in the first half, a deficit that deepened to 45-28 in the second before the Cowboys came around. "I wish I knew why we came out sluggish so we can fix it," said senior guard David Adams. "But I don't know why." After Dabbert, Michael Lindeman had 14 points and Johnny Mathies 12 for the Bluejays. The Cowboys were led by Alex Dunn's 16 points, followed by 10 points from Adams. Wyoming drew within 62-56 when Mikel Watson scored with 1:56 left. Mory Correa then made a free throw and Adams scrambled in a basket to put the Pokes within a 3-pointer. Mathies responded with two free throws for Creighton, then Dunn pulled the Cowboys to 64-61 with 34 seconds left. Tyler McKinney sank two free throws for the Bluejays and Wyoming failed to convert on its last possession. "We need to come out with the energy in the second half that we did in the first," Altman said. "In the first half we had guys flying around the court. In the second half we looked a little bit tired." He wished his team had done better corralling Wyoming's guards. "We knew coming into the game we had to increase the pressure on the UW guards, especially Jay Straight," he said. "We did a good job of doing that in the first half and in the second half we got away from that." Creighton owned most of the game, however, opening the second half with a 13-0 run that included six of Dabbert's points. Wyoming responded with a 14-4 run that cut the Bluejays' lead to 53-42. The Bluejays remained ahead by at least 10 until about 2:30 was left, when a 9-0 run put the Cowboys back in the game. Much of that final run resulted from Wyoming pulling down defensive rebounds. The Cowboys ended with 40 rebounds to the Bluejays' 29. Creighton commanded on shooting, making 47.3 percent to Wyoming's 36.8 percent and leading 35.7 percent to 14.3 percent on 3-pointers. Creighton outscored Wyoming 17-6 in first 10 minutes, getting up 19-8. The Cowboys regained ground to 30-22 and the half ended with a 33-23 Bluejays lead.
